The fourth aspect was defined as ‘staff’ and was broken down into two specific aspects:


a. Approval of the conductor: the quality of the conductor appeared to be an important reason for participation;

b. Approval of the staff: section tutors and house staff were cited as a reason for continued participation. Comments of this type included ‘the tutors and house staff are very friendly and are always great fun to chat to. You are treated as equals by the staff and they are welcome to talk’ and ‘staff are always very friendly and enthusiastic’.

The sixth aspect was ‘benefits’, capturing comments that reflected perceived benefits of participation. This included:


a. Musical benefit, where participation was associated with developments in playing and understanding music;

b. Social benefit, where participation was associated with developments in social skills.
